# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: audio-time-stretching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] These processes are often used to match the pitches and tempos of two pre-recorded clips for mixing when the clips cannot be reperformed or resampled.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Time stretching is often used to adjust radio commercials and the audio of television advertisements to fit exactly into the 30 or 60 seconds available.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] It can be used to conform longer material to a designated time slot, such as a 1-hour broadcast.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] The simplest way to change the duration or pitch of an audio recording is to change the playback speed.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] For a digital audio recording, this can be accomplished through sample rate conversion.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] When using this method, the frequencies in the recording are always scaled at the same ratio as the speed, transposing its pitch up or down in the process.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Slowing down the recording to increase duration also lowers the pitch, while speeding it up for a shorter duration respectively raises the pitch, creating the so-called Chipmunk effect.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] When resampling audio to a notably lower pitch, it may be preferred that the source audio is of a higher sample rate, as slowing down the playback rate will reproduce an audio signal of a lower resolution, and therefore reduce the perceived clarity of the sound.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] When resampling audio to a notably higher pitch, it may be preferred to incorporate an interpolation filter, as frequencies that surpass the Nyquist frequency (determined by the sampling rate of the audio reproduction software or device) will create sound distortions due to aliasing.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] One way of stretching the length of a signal without affecting the pitch is to build a phase vocoder after Flanagan, Golden, and Portnoff.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] 3. perform an inverse STFT by taking the inverse Fourier transform on each chunk and adding the resulting waveform chunks, also called overlap and add (OLA).
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] The phase vocoder handles sinusoid components well, but early implementations introduced considerable smearing on transient ("beat") waveforms at all non-integer compression/expansion rates, which renders the results phasey and diffuse.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Recent improvements allow better quality results at all compression/expansion ratios but a residual smearing effect still remains.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] The phase vocoder technique can also be used to perform pitch shifting, chorusing, timbre manipulation, harmonizing, and other unusual modifications, all of which can be changed as a function of time.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Another method for time stretching relies on a spectral model of the signal.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] In this method, peaks are identified in frames using the STFT of the signal, and sinusoidal "tracks" are created by connecting peaks in adjacent frames.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] The tracks are then re-synthesized at a new time scale.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] This method can yield good results on both polyphonic and percussive material, especially when the signal is separated into sub-bands.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] However, this method is more computationally demanding than other methods.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] This is called time-domain harmonic scaling or the synchronized overlap-add method (SOLA) and performs somewhat faster than the phase vocoder on slower machines but fails when the autocorrelation mis-estimates the period of a signal with complicated harmonics (such as orchestral pieces).
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Adobe Audition (formerly Cool Edit Pro) seems to solve this by looking for the period closest to a center period that the user specifies, which should be an integer multiple of the tempo, and between 30 Hz and the lowest bass frequency.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] This is much more limited in scope than the phase vocoder-based processing, but can be made much less processor intensive, for real-time applications.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] It provides the most coherent results for single-pitched sounds like voice or musically monophonic instrument recordings.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] In order to preserve an audio signal's pitch when stretching or compressing its duration, many time-scale modification (TSM) procedures follow a frame-based approach.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Given an original discrete-time audio signal, this strategy's first step is to split the signal into short **analysis frames** of fixed length.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] The analysis frames are spaced by a fixed number of samples, called the **analysis hopsize** $H_{a}\in \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] To achieve the actual time-scale modification, the analysis frames are then temporally relocated to have a **synthesis hopsize** $H_{s}\in \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] This frame relocation results in a modification of the signal's duration by a **stretching factor** of $\alpha =H_{s}/H_{a}$ .
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] However, simply superimposing the unmodified analysis frames typically results in undesired artifacts such as phase discontinuities or amplitude fluctuations.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] To prevent these kinds of artifacts, the analysis frames are adapted to form **synthesis frames**, prior to the reconstruction of the time-scale modified output signal.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] The strategy for deriving the synthesis frames from the analysis frames is a key difference among different TSM procedures.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] For the specific case of speech, time stretching can be performed using PSOLA.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Time-compressed speech is the representation of verbal text in compressed time.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Listening to time-compressed speech is seen as the equivalent of speed reading.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] These techniques can also be used to transpose an audio sample while holding speed or duration constant.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] This may be accomplished by time stretching and then resampling back to the original length.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Alternatively, the frequency of the sinusoids in a sinusoidal model may be altered directly, and the signal reconstructed at the appropriate time scale.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Transposing can be called *frequency scaling* or *pitch shifting*, depending on perspective.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] For example, one could move the pitch of every note up by a perfect fifth, keeping the tempo the same.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] One can view this transposition as "pitch shifting", "shifting" each note up 7 keys on a piano keyboard, or adding a fixed amount on the Mel scale, or adding a fixed amount in linear pitch space.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] One can view the same transposition as "frequency scaling", "scaling" (multiplying) the frequency of every note by 3/2.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Musical transposition preserves the ratios of the harmonic frequencies that determine the sound's timbre, unlike the *frequency shift* performed by amplitude modulation, which adds a fixed frequency offset to the frequency of every note.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Time domain processing works much better here, as smearing is less noticeable, but scaling vocal samples distorts the formants into a sort of Alvin and the Chipmunks-like effect, which may be desirable or undesirable.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] A process that preserves the formants and character of a voice involves analyzing the signal with a channel vocoder or LPC vocoder plus any of several pitch detection algorithms and then resynthesizing it at a different fundamental frequency.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] A detailed description of older analog recording techniques for pitch shifting can be found at Alvin and the Chipmunks § Recording technique.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Time stretching and pitch scaling is used extensively by DJs in addition to beatmixing when playing and creating a set.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] In order to seamlessly blend two tracks together, the tempo of a track can be adjusted to match another track such that the beats line up.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Pitch scaling is commonly used to retain the pitch of a track.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Pitch scaling is also used by DJs for harmonic mixing, to transform tracks into compatible keys so that they sound pleasing when mixed together.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Time stretching and pitch scaling are included in modern DJ hardware (CDJs and DJ controllers) and software (such as VirtualDJ, Mixxx, Serato and Rekordbox).
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Time stretching and pitch scaling is used in digital audio workstation software for working with music loops, sound clips which can be repeated and transposed to form a song.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] The pitch and tempo of multiple loops are aligned to create tracks.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Notable software includes Acid Pro with its "Acidized" loops feature and FL Studio.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Pitch-corrected audio timestretch is found in every modern web browser as part of the HTML standard for media playback.
[src:audio-time-stretching/audio-time-stretching-and-pitch-scaling] Similar controls are ubiquitous in media applications and frameworks such as GStreamer and Unity.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] A **phase vocoder** is a type of vocoder-purposed algorithm which can interpolate information present in the frequency and time domains of audio signals by using phase information extracted from a frequency transform.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The computer algorithm allows frequency-domain modifications to a digital sound file (typically time expansion/compression and pitch shifting).
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] At the heart of the phase vocoder is the short-time Fourier transform (STFT), typically coded using fast Fourier transforms.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The time evolution of the resynthesized sound can be changed by means of modifying the time position of the STFT frames prior to the resynthesis operation allowing for time-scale modification of the original sound file.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The main problem that has to be solved for all cases of manipulation of the STFT is the fact that individual signal components (sinusoids, impulses) will be spread over multiple frames and multiple STFT frequency locations (bins).
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] This is because the STFT analysis is done using overlapping analysis windows.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The windowing results in spectral leakage such that the information of individual sinusoidal components is spread over adjacent STFT bins.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] To avoid border effects of tapering of the analysis windows, STFT analysis windows overlap in time.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] This time overlap results in the fact that adjacent STFT analyses are strongly correlated (a sinusoid present in analysis frame at time "t" will be present in the subsequent frames as well).
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The problem of signal transformation with the phase vocoder is related to the problem that all modifications that are done in the STFT representation need to preserve the appropriate correlation between adjacent frequency bins (vertical coherence) and time frames (horizontal coherence).
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The phase coherence problem was investigated for quite a while before appropriate solutions emerged.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The phase vocoder was introduced in 1966 by Flanagan as an algorithm that would preserve horizontal coherence between the phases of bins that represent sinusoidal components.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] This original phase vocoder did not take into account the vertical coherence between adjacent frequency bins, and therefore, time stretching with this system produced sound signals that were missing clarity.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The optimal reconstruction of the sound signal from STFT after amplitude modifications has been proposed by Griffin and Lim in 1984.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] This algorithm does not consider the problem of producing a coherent STFT, but it does allow finding the sound signal that has an STFT that is as close as possible to the modified STFT even if the modified STFT is not coherent (does not represent any signal).
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The problem of the vertical coherence remained a major issue for the quality of time scaling operations until 1999 when Laroche and Dolson proposed a means to preserve phase consistency across spectral bins.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The proposition of Laroche and Dolson has to be seen as a turning point in phase vocoder history.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] It has been shown that by means of ensuring vertical phase consistency very high quality time scaling transformations can be obtained.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The algorithm proposed by Laroche did not allow preservation of vertical phase coherence for sound onsets (note onsets).
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] A solution for this problem has been proposed by Roebel.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] An example of software implementation of phase vocoder based signal transformation using means similar to those described here to achieve high quality signal transformation is Ircam's SuperVP.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] British composer Trevor Wishart used phase vocoder analyses and transformations of a human voice as the basis for his composition *Vox 5* (part of his larger Vox Cycle).
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] *Transfigured Wind* by American composer Roger Reynolds uses the phase vocoder to perform time-stretching of flute sounds.
[src:audio-time-stretching/phase-vocoder] The music of JoAnn Kuchera-Morin makes some of the earliest and most extensive use of phase vocoder transformations, such as in *Dreampaths* (1989).
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] In signal processing, **sampling** is the reduction of a continuous-time signal to a discrete-time signal.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] A common example is the conversion of a sound wave to a sequence of "samples".
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] A **sample** is a value of the signal at a point in time and/or space; this definition differs from the term's usage in statistics, which refers to a set of such values.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] A **sampler** is a subsystem or operation that extracts samples from a continuous signal.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] A theoretical **ideal sampler** produces samples equivalent to the instantaneous value of the continuous signal at the desired points.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The original signal can be reconstructed from a sequence of samples, up to the Nyquist limit, by passing the sequence of samples through a reconstruction filter.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Functions of space, time, or any other dimension can be sampled, and similarly in two or more dimensions.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] For functions that vary with time, let $s(t)$ be a continuous function (or "signal") to be sampled, and let sampling be performed by measuring the value of the continuous function every T seconds, which is called the **sampling interval** or **sampling period**.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The **sampling frequency** or **sampling rate**, $f_{s}$ , is the average number of samples obtained in one second, thus $f_{s}=1/T$ , with the unit *samples per second*, sometimes referred to as hertz, for example 48 kHz is 48,000 *samples per second*.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Reconstructing a continuous function from samples is done by interpolation algorithms.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula is mathematically equivalent to an ideal low-pass filter whose input is a sequence of Dirac delta functions that are modulated (multiplied) by the sample values.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] When the time interval between adjacent samples is a constant $(T)$ , the sequence of delta functions is called a Dirac comb.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Mathematically, the modulated Dirac comb is equivalent to the product of the comb function with $s(t)$ .
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] That mathematical abstraction is sometimes referred to as *impulse sampling*.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Most sampled signals are not simply stored and reconstructed.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The fidelity of a theoretical reconstruction is a common measure of the effectiveness of sampling.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] That fidelity is reduced when $s(t)$ contains frequency components whose cycle length (period) is less than 2 sample intervals (see *Aliasing*).
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The corresponding frequency limit, in *cycles per second* (hertz), is $0.5$ cycle/sample × $f_{s}$ samples/second = $f_{s}/2$ , known as the Nyquist frequency of the sampler.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Therefore, $s(t)$ is usually the output of a low-pass filter, functionally known as an *anti-aliasing filter*.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Without an anti-aliasing filter, frequencies higher than the Nyquist frequency will influence the samples in a way that is misinterpreted by the interpolation process.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] In practice, the continuous signal is sampled using an analog-to-digital converter (ADC), a device with various physical limitations.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] This results in deviations from the theoretically perfect reconstruction, collectively referred to as distortion.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Although the use of oversampling can completely eliminate aperture error and aliasing by shifting them out of the passband, this technique cannot be practically used above a few GHz, and may be prohibitively expensive at much lower frequencies.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Furthermore, while oversampling can reduce quantization error and non-linearity, it cannot eliminate these entirely.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Consequently, practical ADCs at audio frequencies typically do not exhibit aliasing or aperture error, and are not limited by quantization error.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] At RF and microwave frequencies, where oversampling is impractical and filters are expensive, aperture error, quantization error and aliasing can be significant limitations.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Jitter, noise, and quantization are often analyzed by modeling them as random errors added to the sample values.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Integration and zero-order hold effects can be analyzed as a form of low-pass filtering.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The non-linearities of either ADC or DAC are analyzed by replacing the ideal linear function mapping with a proposed nonlinear function.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Digital audio systems typically employ pulse-code modulation (PCM) to encode sound as a series of discrete samples of the electrical level of an analog audio signal.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Analog signals are captured (encoded) as PCM samples in analog-to-digital conversion (ADC), and reproduced (decoded) using digital-to-analog conversion (DAC).
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The encoding used for the storage and transmission of digitised sound data within the system may differ.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] When it is necessary to capture audio covering the entire 20–20,000 Hz range of human hearing such as when recording music or many types of acoustic events, audio waveforms are typically sampled at 44.1 kHz (CD), 48 kHz, 88.2 kHz, or 96 kHz.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The approximately double-rate requirement is a consequence of the Nyquist theorem.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Sampling rates higher than about 50 kHz to 60 kHz cannot supply more usable information for human listeners.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Early professional audio equipment manufacturers chose sampling rates in the region of 40 to 50 kHz for this reason.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Conversely, ultrasonic sounds may interact with and modulate the audible part of the frequency spectrum (intermodulation distortion), *degrading* the fidelity.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] One advantage of higher sampling rates is that they can relax the low-pass filter design requirements for ADCs and DACs, but with modern oversampling delta-sigma-converters, this advantage is less important.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The Audio Engineering Society recommends 48 kHz sampling rate for most applications, but gives recognition to 44.1 kHz for CD and other consumer uses, 32 kHz for transmission-related applications, and 96 kHz for higher bandwidth or relaxed anti-aliasing filtering.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Robert Stuart state that the ideal sampling rate would be about 60 kHz, but since this is not a standard frequency, recommend 88.2 or 96 kHz for recording purposes.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Audio is typically recorded at 8-, 16-, and 24-bit depth; which yield a theoretical maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio (SQNR) for a pure sine wave of, approximately; 49.93 dB, 98.09 dB, and 122.17 dB.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Thermal noise limits the true number of bits that can be used in quantization.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Few analog systems have signal to noise ratios (SNR) exceeding 120 dB.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] However, digital signal processing operations can have very high dynamic range, consequently, it is common to perform mixing and mastering operations at 32-bit floating-point precision and then convert to 16- or 24-bit for distribution.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Speech signals, i.e., signals intended to carry only human speech, can usually be sampled at a much lower rate.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] For most phonemes, almost all of the energy is contained in the 100 Hz – 4 kHz range, allowing a sampling rate of 8 kHz.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] This is the sampling rate used by nearly all telephony systems, which use the G.711 sampling and quantization specifications.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Standard-definition television (SDTV) uses either 720 by 480 pixels (US NTSC 525-line) or 720 by 576 pixels (UK PAL 625-line) for the visible picture area.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] High-definition television (HDTV) uses 720p (progressive), 1080i (interlaced), and 1080p (progressive, also known as Full-HD).
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] In digital video, the temporal sampling rate is defined as the frame rate – or rather the field rate – rather than the notional pixel clock.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The image sampling frequency is the repetition rate of the sensor integration period.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Video digital-to-analog converters operate in the megahertz range (from ~3 MHz for low-quality composite video scalers in early game consoles, to 250 MHz or more for the highest-resolution VGA output).
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] When analog video is converted to digital video, a different sampling process occurs, this time at the pixel frequency, corresponding to a spatial sampling rate along scan lines.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Spatial sampling in the other direction is determined by the spacing of scan lines in the raster.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The sampling rates and resolutions in both spatial directions can be measured in units of lines per picture height.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Spatial aliasing of high-frequency luma or chroma video components shows up as a moiré pattern.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The process of volume rendering samples a 3D grid of voxels to produce 3D renderings of sliced (tomographic) data.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The 3D grid is assumed to represent a continuous region of 3D space.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Volume rendering is common in medical imaging, X-ray computed tomography (CT/CAT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), positron emission tomography (PET) are some examples.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] It is also used for seismic tomography and other applications.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] When a bandpass signal is sampled slower than its Nyquist rate, the samples are indistinguishable from samples of a low-frequency alias of the high-frequency signal.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] That is often done purposefully in such a way that the lowest-frequency alias satisfies the Nyquist criterion, because the bandpass signal is still uniquely represented and recoverable.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Oversampling is used in most modern analog-to-digital converters to reduce the distortion introduced by practical digital-to-analog converters, such as a zero-order hold instead of idealizations like the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Although complex-valued samples can be obtained as described above, they are also created by manipulating samples of a real-valued waveform.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] For instance, the equivalent baseband waveform can be created without explicitly computing ${\hat {s}}(t)$ , by processing the product sequence, $\left[s(nT)\cdot e^{-i2\pi {\frac {B}{2}}Tn}\right]$ , through a digital low-pass filter whose cutoff frequency is $B/2$ .
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] Computing only every other sample of the output sequence reduces the sample rate commensurate with the reduced Nyquist rate.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] The result is half as many complex-valued samples as the original number of real samples.
[src:audio-time-stretching/sampling-signal-processing] No information is lost, and the original $s(t)$ waveform can be recovered, if necessary.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The **short-time Fourier transform** (**STFT**) is a Fourier-related transform used to determine the sinusoidal frequency and phase content of local sections of a signal as it changes over time.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] In practice, the procedure for computing STFTs is to divide a longer time signal into shorter segments of equal length and then compute the Fourier transform separately on each shorter segment.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] This reveals the Fourier spectrum on each shorter segment.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] One then usually plots the changing spectra as a function of time, known as a spectrogram or waterfall plot, such as commonly used in software defined radio (SDR) based spectrum displays.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Full bandwidth displays covering the whole range of an SDR commonly use fast Fourier transforms (FFTs).
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Simply, in the continuous-time case, the function to be transformed is multiplied by a window function which is nonzero for only a short period of time.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The Fourier transform (a one-dimensional function) of the resulting signal is taken, then the window is slid along the time axis until the end resulting in a two-dimensional representation of the signal.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Often phase unwrapping is employed along either or both the time axis, $\tau$ , and frequency axis, $\omega$ , to suppress any jump discontinuity of the phase result of the STFT.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The time index $\tau$ is normally considered to be "*slow*" time and usually not expressed in as high resolution as time t .
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Given that the STFT is essentially a Fourier transform times a window function, the STFT is also called windowed Fourier transform or time-dependent Fourier transform.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] In the discrete time case, the data to be transformed could be broken up into chunks or frames (which usually overlap each other, to reduce artifacts at the boundary).
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Each chunk is Fourier transformed, and the complex result is added to a matrix, which records magnitude and phase for each point in time and frequency.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] likewise, with signal $x[n]$ and window $w[n]$ .
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] In this case, *m* is discrete and ω is continuous, but in most typical applications the STFT is performed on a computer using the fast Fourier transform, so both variables are discrete and quantized.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] See also the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), which is also a Fourier-related transform that uses overlapping windows.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] If only a small number of ω are desired, or if the STFT is desired to be evaluated for every shift *m* of the window, then the STFT may be more efficiently evaluated using a sliding DFT algorithm.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The STFT is invertible, that is, the original signal can be recovered from the transform by the inverse STFT.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The most widely accepted way of inverting the STFT is by using the overlap-add (OLA) method, which also allows for modifications to the STFT complex spectrum.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] This makes for a versatile signal processing method, referred to as the *overlap and add with modifications* method.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] So the Fourier transform can be seen as a sort of phase coherent sum of all of the STFTs of *x*(*t*).
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] the inverse Fourier transform of *X*(τ,ω) for τ fixed.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] One of the pitfalls of the STFT is that it has a fixed resolution.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The width of the windowing function relates to how the signal is represented—it determines whether there is good frequency resolution (frequency components close together can be separated) or good time resolution (the time at which frequencies change).
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] A wide window gives better frequency resolution but poor time resolution.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] A narrower window gives good time resolution but poor frequency resolution.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] These are called narrowband and wideband transforms, respectively.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] This is one of the reasons for the creation of the wavelet transform and multiresolution analysis, which can give good time resolution for high-frequency events and good frequency resolution for low-frequency events, the combination best suited for many real signals.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] This property is related to the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, but not directly – see Gabor limit for discussion.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The product of the standard deviation in time and frequency is limited.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The boundary of the uncertainty principle (best simultaneous resolution of both) is reached with a Gaussian window function (or mask function), as the Gaussian minimizes the Fourier uncertainty principle.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] This is called the Gabor transform (and with modifications for multiresolution becomes the Morlet wavelet transform).
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] One can consider the STFT for varying window size as a two-dimensional domain (time and frequency), as illustrated in the example below, which can be calculated by varying the window size.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] However, this is no longer a strictly time-frequency representation – the kernel is not constant over the entire signal.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Using the following sample signal $x(t)$ that is composed of a set of four sinusoidal waveforms joined together in sequence.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Each waveform is only composed of one of four frequencies (10, 25, 50, 100 Hz).
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The 25 ms window allows us to identify a precise time at which the signals change but the precise frequencies are difficult to identify.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] At the other end of the scale, the 1000 ms window allows the frequencies to be precisely seen but the time between frequency changes is blurred.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Normally we call $exp(\sigma -t^{2})$ a Gaussian function or Gabor function.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] When we use it, the short-time Fourier transform is called the "Gabor transform".
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] It can also be explained with reference to the sampling and Nyquist frequency.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Take a window of *N* samples from an arbitrary real-valued signal at sampling rate *f*s .
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Taking the Fourier transform produces *N* complex coefficients.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Of these coefficients only half are useful (the last *N/2* being the complex conjugate of the first *N/2* in reverse order, as this is a real valued signal).
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] These *N/2* coefficients represent the frequencies 0 to *f*s/2 (Nyquist) and two consecutive coefficients are spaced apart by *f*s/*N* Hz.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] To increase the frequency resolution of the window the frequency spacing of the coefficients needs to be reduced.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] There are only two variables, but decreasing *f*s (and keeping *N* constant) will cause the window size to increase — since there are now fewer samples per unit time.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The other alternative is to increase *N*, but this again causes the window size to increase.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] So any attempt to increase the frequency resolution causes a larger window size and therefore a reduction in time resolution—and vice versa.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] As the Nyquist frequency is a limitation in the maximum frequency that can be meaningfully analysed, so is the Rayleigh frequency a limitation on the minimum frequency.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The Rayleigh frequency is the minimum frequency that can be resolved by a finite duration time window.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Given a time window that is Τ seconds long, the minimum frequency that can be resolved is 1/Τ Hz.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The Rayleigh frequency is an important consideration in applications of the short-time Fourier transform (STFT), as well as any other method of harmonic analysis on a signal of finite record-length.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] STFTs as well as standard Fourier transforms and other tools are frequently used to analyze music.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The spectrogram can, for example, show frequency on the horizontal axis, with the lowest frequencies at left, and the highest at the right.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The height of each bar (augmented by color) represents the amplitude of the frequencies within that band.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] The depth dimension represents time, where each new bar was a separate distinct transform.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] Audio engineers use this kind of visual to gain information about an audio sample, for example, to locate the frequencies of specific noises (especially when used with greater frequency resolution) or to find frequencies which may be more or less resonant in the space where the signal was recorded.
[src:audio-time-stretching/short-time-fourier-transform] This information can be used for equalization or tuning other audio effects.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] In electronics, acoustics, and related fields, the **waveform** of a signal is the shape of its graph as a function of time, independent of its time and magnitude scales and of any displacement in time.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] *Periodic waveforms* repeat regularly at a constant period.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] The term can also be used for non-periodic or aperiodic signals, like chirps and pulses.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] In electronics, the term is usually applied to time-varying voltages, currents, or electromagnetic fields.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] In acoustics, it is usually applied to steady periodic sounds — variations of pressure in air or other media.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] In these cases, the waveform is an attribute that is independent of the frequency, amplitude, or phase shift of the signal.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] The waveform of an electrical signal can be visualized with an oscilloscope or any other device that can capture and plot its value at various times, with suitable scales in the time and value axes.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] The electrocardiograph is a medical device to record the waveform of the electric signals that are associated with the beating of the heart; that waveform has important diagnostic value.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] Waveform generators, which can output a periodic voltage or current with one of several waveforms, are a common tool in electronics laboratories and workshops.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] The waveform of a steady periodic sound affects its timbre.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] Synthesizers and modern keyboards can generate sounds with many complex waveforms.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] The Fourier series describes the decomposition of periodic waveforms, such that any periodic waveform can be formed by the sum of a (possibly infinite) set of fundamental and harmonic components.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] Finite-energy non-periodic waveforms can be analyzed into sinusoids by the Fourier transform.
[src:audio-time-stretching/waveform] Other periodic waveforms are often called composite waveforms and can often be described as a combination of a number of sinusoidal waves or other basis functions added together.
